    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">Hi everyone, today I bring you some ES6 magic for common Array algorithms that sometimes, we overthink, and they have a really easy one-lined solution using high order functions like filter and <strong>Set theory.</strong></p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">What in the world is Set theory? Just a branch of <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mathematical_logic" target="_self">mathematical logic</a> that studies <a href="https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Set_(mathematics)" target="_self">sets</a>, which informally are collections of objects. We are not covering the same methods for <strong>Javascript Sets</strong> (Arrays and Sets are different data structures, you can take a look in this article to understand it better <a href="https://medium.com/front-end-hacking/es6-set-vs-array-what-and-when-efc055655e1a" target="_self">https://medium.com/front-end-hacking/es6-set-vs-array-what-and-when-efc055655e1a</a>) but because Arrays are collections of homogeneous data, will be the same principle.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">In this article, you will learn to implement these features.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-5">Code</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">For all the examples, we have two arrays, <em>A </em><code>arrA=[1,3,4,5]</code><em> </em>& <code>arrB=[1,2,5,6,7]</code>, we need a third array called <em>C </em>with the results of the operation. Let’s use some <em>Venn Diagrams</em> to help us visualize the concepts.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
